Date:  0/0/1874
Source:  Colonial Experiences
Author:  BATHGATE
Vol / Page:  197
Edition:
Quote:   [in Otago] a `hundred' and the land is then opened up for sale at 1 [pound] per acre.... The purchases of land within a `hundred' have the exclusive privilege of depasturing stock upon the unsold lands within the `hundred' in proportion to their purchased property. A small fee or assessment of so much per head, is paid to the Government for this privilege. [Until the land is sold. All land unsold after a few years may be brought at ten shillings per acre]
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1898
Source:  Contributions to the Early History of New Zealand
Author:  HOCKEN
Vol / Page:  167
Edition:
Quote:  The old Otago Block had already been divided into Hundreds, at first three in number, but was now subdivided for greater convenience into eight. The first extended from the Heads to the Taieri river, ... Within these Hundreds the rural lands were open for sale at 10s. and acre, with the  40s. improvement conditions. Outside them were 600,000 acres, open for sale at  10s. an acre, in blocks of not less than 2000 acres, without the improvement clause.
